<br>
Consubstantial <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#001B55><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bslipstreambbs12353.showUserPublicProfile?gid=osiris@slipstreambbs12353>Osiris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#EFD68C>(1/17/03 9:08:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fslipstreambbs12353frm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Post editing</span><hr size=1> Unless otherwise stated, the content of message board posts becomes the property of the board owner, except in the case of previously copyrighted material (which normally must carry a copyright notice). Owners can be held responsible for content appearing on a board or in a chat room. That's why many boards have disclaimer notices attached to them, saying that &quot;the views expressed on this board are not necessarily the views of [the board owner].&quot; <br>
<br>
Editing posts, therefore, is at the discretion of the owner of the board. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3eyes</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> made the point that it seems more ethical to allow a user to change his or her own post. I would agree, but only if they're readily available to do so, which they often aren't. 24 hours is a lot of time for offensive or damaging information to be posted. Most people check in at least once a day, and would probably read it, so what would be the benefit of removing it after a 24-hour period? Sometimes it's necessary to edit a post to remove such information immediately. Therefore, I would agree with <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>HF</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that editing out a line or two is a quick and effective means of dealing with problematic posts. It's not a question of legality, but practicality.<br>
<br>
Osiris <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003B75><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bslipstreambbs12353.showUserPublicProfile?gid=threeeyesopen>three eyes open</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#EFD68C>(1/17/03 10:57:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fslipstreambbs12353frm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: On flaming</span><hr size=1> Unless it is *specifically* stated in the TOS of using a board, anything that can possibly be qualified as a piece of fiction, poetry, song, essay or artwork is automatically copyrighted by the composer, no matter who or what company may own the BBS or website.<br>
<br>
Now, the definition of what qualifies for that label is very, very gray. Even rants made by peope on the internet have been designated as essays and thus qualified as copyrighted works.  <br>
<br>
So you see, editing something that even contains insults directed at another individual can be very tricky (especially one that uses a certain individual as an example). A case could possibly made that many, many posts on a message board are essentially essays of the author's thoughts.<br>
<br>
In the eT/Starlock case, both were correct in that their works were copyrighted; that was a dispute between artists in the eyes of the law.<br>
<br>
If the law wasn't so clear about this, I wouldn't publish even four lines of verse on the internet, let alone whole stories.<br>
<br>
If you are unsure about this, you can contact Agent Philip Davidson of the FBI, who explained this to me.<br>
<br>
BB,<br>
